Step 1: Create Project Folder
mkdir java-docker-hello
cd java-docker-hello

Step 2: Create the Java Program
nano HelloWorld.java
Paste this code and save it (Ctrl + O → Enter → Ctrl + X):

public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World from Docker!");
    }
}

Step 3: Create the Dockerfile
nano Dockerfile
Paste the following content:  .....

# Step 1: Use an official OpenJDK base image
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim

# Step 2: Set working directory inside container
WORKDIR /app

# Step 3: Copy Java source code into container
COPY HelloWorld.java /app

# Step 4: Compile the Java code
RUN javac HelloWorld.java

# Step 5: Run the compiled class
CMD ["java", "HelloWorld"]

....
Save and exit.

Step 4: Build the Docker Image
docker build -t hello-java .
Output (example):
Successfully built 2f3b6f7c1234
Successfully tagged hello-java:latest

Step 5: Run the Docker Container
docker run --rm hello-java
Output:
Hello, World from Docker!


Your Java app is successfully running inside Docker.

Step 6: Log in to Docker Hub
docker login
Enter your Docker Hub username and password (or access token).

Step 7: Tag Your Image for Docker Hub
docker tag hello-java <your-dockerhub-username>/hello-java:latest
Example:
docker tag hello-java shweta01/hello-java:latest

Step 8: Push Image to Docker Hub
docker push <your-dockerhub-username>/hello-java:latest
Example:
docker push shweta01/hello-java:latest

Step 9: Verify Your Image on Docker Hub
Go to:
https://hub.docker.com/repository/docker/<your-dockerhub-username>/hello-java
Example:
https://hub.docker.com/repository/docker/shweta01/hello-java

Step 10: Pull & Run From Anywhere
From any system with Docker installed:
docker run --rm <your-dockerhub-username>/hello-java:latest
Example:
docker run --rm shweta01/hello-java:latest

Output:
Hello, World from Docker!
